<seg id="1042">If a picture is rendered with only one beam per pixel, various errors can occur. these images often have a Moirè pattern or tier effects in curves and lines, and sometimes details are not shown when they are less than a pixel. this effect is called aliasing.</seg>
<seg id="1043">& Povray; uses a technique called anti-aliasing to decrease the impact of these errors. generally, pictures with this feature look better.</seg>
<seg id="1044">When you switch on anti-aliasing, calculates and connects & Povray; more than one beam per pixel. this technique is called super-sampling.</seg>
<seg id="1045">& Povray; supports two methods of super-sampling. as standard is an adaptive, non-recursive method; adaptively because the super-sampling reads the adjacent pixels. the second method is adaptive, recursively because each pixel is divided further and further, because the recursion depth depends on the calculated colour values.</seg>
<seg id="1046">If you choose the first method, POV-Ray tracks a beam per pixel. if the difference between the color values to the adjacent pixels exceeds the specified threshold, then both pixels are calculated by tracking a certain additional number of pixels with super-sampling. if you set the depth value to 4, a grid of 4 will be calculated, at a depth value of 5 then 5x5 (25) additional rays per pixel.</seg>
<seg id="1047">The difference between two pixels is calculated as follows: r 1, g 1 and b 1 are the values for red, green and blue of the first pixel, r 2, g 2 and b 2 are the values for red, green and blue of the second pixel. the difference then is:</seg>
<seg id="1048">Diff = abs (r 1 -r 2) + abs (g 1 -g 2) + abs (b 1 -b 2)</seg>
<seg id="1049">The recursive method starts with 4 rays per pixel. if the difference between the color values exceeds the specified threshold, the pixel is divided into 4 sub-pixels, which are further followed and tested for further subdivisions. the maximum depth of the recursion can be adjusted with the depth value.</seg>
